SIMPLE: tissue
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tissue
<hw>Tis"sue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>tissu</ets>,
fr. <ets>tissu</ets>, p. p. of <ets>tisser</ets>, <ets>tistre</ets>, to
weave, fr. L. <ets>texere</ets>. See <er>Text</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A woven fabric.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A fine transparent silk stuff, used for veils, etc.;
specifically, cloth interwoven with gold or silver threads, or embossed
with figures.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A robe of <qex>tissue</qex>, stiff with golden wire.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In their glittering <qex>tissues</qex> bear emblazed⟦br⟧
Holy memorials.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>One of the elementary materials
or fibres, having a uniform structure and a specialized function, of
which ordinary animals and plants are composed; a texture; <as>as,
epithelial <ex>tissue</ex>; connective <ex>tissue</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The term <xex>tissue</xex> is also often applied in a
wider sense to all the materials or elementary tissues, differing in
structure and function, which go to make up an organ; as, vascular
<xex>tissue</xex>, tegumentary <xex>tissue</xex>, etc.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Fig.: Web; texture; complicated fabrication;
connected series; <as>as, a <ex>tissue</ex> of forgeries, or of
falsehood</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Unwilling to leave the dry bones of Agnosticism wholly unclothed
with any living <qex>tissue</qex> of religious emotion.</q> <rj><qau>A.
J. Balfour.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Tissue paper</b></col>, <cd>very thin, gauzelike paper,
used for protecting engravings in books, for wrapping up delicate
articles, etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tissue</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tissue
<hw>Tis"sue</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Tissued</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tissuing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To form tissue of; to
interweave.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Covered with cloth of gold <qex>tissued</qex> upon blue.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tissued</ent>⟦br⟧
